post_text:
As we move deeper in to the school year it is imperative for everyone to understand how eligibility will work for athletics and activities.

Due to the situation in the spring all students were granted eligibility at the start of this school year. Moving forward eligibility will be reestablished based on the first quarter of this school year.

This means that students must have a 2.0 and cannot have any F’s on the 1st quarter report card. We want everyone to understand this so when it comes time for us to begin athletics and activities that are sanctioned by the NMAA, we understand that eligibility does count. For the 2nd semester normal eligibility will be resumed.

Breakfast and Lunch meals can be picked up between 11:00 and 12:00 at Aztec High School, Lydia Rippey, McCoy and First Baptist Church.

12:30 – 12:50 Cedar Hill Fire Station, Crouch Mesa Baptist Church and Round Valley 3450/3451

Thank you for all your support of our Foodservice program over the past several months. Now that school is open, we want to remind everyone that we are still providing meals on bus routes and in the community.

We are serving from 11:00 AM – 12:00 PM at McCoy Elementary, Lydia Rippey Elementary, Aztec High School and First Baptist Church.

We also have buses that run between 11:00 - 12:50 at sites around the district. Meals are available for students enrolled in Aztec Schools and Mosaic Charter School. If you have a student in McCoy, Rippey, Park or Vista Nueva, those students are all served meals free of charge. If students are from Koogler, AHS and Mosaic, they will need to complete a new application for Free and Reduced meals. Those can be picked up at any school or the Administration Building. We look forward to serving all our students across the district. If you have any questions, please feel free to reach out to the Foodservice office at 599-4351.

~~~~Aztec Schools Foodservice Office.

Bob Schryver
Food Service Director
Aztec Municipal Schools
505-599-4351

We will have to record meals served as Paid, Free and Reduced. We will need the students/parents to give us the student name and what school they attend so we can record the meals accurately. As always, if you have any questions, please feel free to call the food service office at 505-599-4351.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians:

The purpose of this correspondence is to inform you that our on-line learning program for the elementary level will be changing. Originally the district had planned to use the K-12 program for our students in grades K-5 who opted for online only. We were informed today that the Public Education Department is reducing our funding. For this reason, we are now going to offer total online instruction provided by Aztec teachers via Google classroom. It will be called AMSD Online Learning. Instruction for the AMSD on-line program will begin on August 10, 2020.
We will still provide devices for this program if you need them. We will also provide technology support as needed. We hope that using Aztec teachers to provide online instruction will make our students and parents more comfortable with online learning.

Again thank you for considering the AMSD online program.

“There is not elevator to success, you have to take the stairs.”

WE ARE AZTEC

WE GOT THIS!

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians.

As we continue to work and get feedback, we wanted to update you on another key decision in our plan. As you know, we will be doing an A-B split in our Face to Face Instruction. Group A students will be attending school for face to face instruction on Mondays and Tuesdays. Group B Students will attend school for face to face instruction on Wednesdays and Thursdays. We are in the process of assigning students to these groups. Families will be assigned to the same group.

We know that much of our information is coming out in pieces, but we want to do all we can to keep you updated in a timely fashion.

We are also working on our Reentry document which will capture this and all other information and requirements that will be coming out and be available in the near future as well.

Thank you,

Superintendent Carpenter

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians:

We have received a lot of questions around our reentry plan. We are still working on this plan and will be finalizing it in the next couple of weeks. In fact, we will be calling you next week to get another important question answered from you on what your plans are for your son or daughter, so we can put some final details together. Please know that a staff member will be calling.

We have posted a Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) document on our website for you to review. As much as we are trying to stay on top of all the questions coming in, we just cannot manage all of them. We have tried to address the most common ones on this document. We will continue to monitor Facebook and update this document.

We appreciate your patience and know that one important action is our Board of Education will be adopting the adjusted calendar for next school year.

Thanks, Kirk

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians:
As you all know we have been given direction from the Public Education Department on how we will be able to open our schools in the Fall of 2020. That being said we are in the process of developing our reopening plan that meets the requirements and falls within the guidelines as outlined by the PED. We would like to have some feedback from you. We are on a tight turnaround so we need your input completed and back to us by Monday July 6, 2020. Please tell anyone you know who has students in Aztec Schools about this survey link. We are sending it out to all of our parents, and posting it on our Facebook Page, but we also know that people relocate and emails and cell phone numbers change. Our goal is to get feedback and as much of it as possible.

We are working hard on this issue and trying to make the best plan we can within the boundaries we must work in, for the benefit of all stakeholders.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/DQG6KHY

Thank you,

Superintendent Carpenter

We are excited to let you know that starting today we will be highlighting our amazing Honor Graduates on our website. You will be able to find them on our Spotlight page. We plan to highlight two a day with information on what their plans are for next year, what they seen themselves doing in their future, favorite memory from their educational career and a teacher or teachers that impacted them over the years while in the district.

We are very proud of their accomplishments and know that they are destined to do great things.

Thanks

Kirk Carpenter

Another great series with Ron and this time our talented Lauren Laws, Principal from Park Avenue Elementary School. Ron and Lauren talk about Hidden Issues and the importance of getting to what really is the problem when trying to solve problems.

One other things to note. Some of the videos are choppy at times, but they do smooth out. It is due to a high volume of internet use around the country. Don’t give up on them and if you have trouble with the link go to our Facebook page.

Thank you for your continued work and for being who you are, because we appreciate you just like you are and for who you are.

Enjoy and and as again please share with family.

Kirk

Greetings Aztec Staff: I first of all want to tell you thank you for impacting our students. Also that we appreciate all you have done. We are on the home stretch as we have started the Month of May. Now is the time to reach deep and remind our students to do the same. Let our best learning happen between now and tomorrow and lets repeat that process until May 22, 2020.

Below you will find the link to the Aztec Connects Series 6. It is on making deposits into the Emotional Bank Account and Button Guard. Our special guest for this episode is our very own Board President Roger Collins. We thank him for taking time to be with us and as always thank Ron for giving us another tool to help us improve what we do in communicating in everyday life.

Have a great day.

Superintendent Carpenter

post_text:
This Friday as you know is May 1st. In honor of the Aztec Class of 2020, which includes all our seniors from Aztec High School and Vista Nueva High School, we are declaring the month of May “Class of 2020 Month.”

We have a lot of things planned for them, yes many of them from a distance, but fun none the less. Details are coming. We are working on a formal joint proclamation/resolution between the City of Aztec and our School Board to honor our Seniors. We hope to have that adopted by both entities by May 14th.

To start off the month in honor of the class of 2020 we are asking all residents to turn porch lights on this Friday night at 8:20 p.m. and leave them on overnight until 5:40 a.m.

Why these times? 8:20 is 20 minutes after sunset, 5:40 is 20 minutes before sunrise. This represents 2020.

And to the Class of 2020, you are almost there. Keep working hard and make this month, in your honor, count.

Superintendent Carpenter
text:
This Friday as you know is May 1st. In honor of the Aztec Class of 2020, which includes all our seniors from Aztec High School and Vista Nueva High School, we are declaring the month of May “Class of 2020 Month.”

We have a lot of things planned for them, yes many of them from a distance, but fun none the less. Details are coming. We are working on a formal joint proclamation/resolution between the City of Aztec and our School Board to honor our Seniors. We hope to have that adopted by both entities by May 14th.

To start off the month in honor of the class of 2020 we are asking all residents to turn porch lights on this Friday night at 8:20 p.m. and leave them on overnight until 5:40 a.m.

Why these times? 8:20 is 20 minutes after sunset, 5:40 is 20 minutes before sunrise. This represents 2020.

And to the Class of 2020, you are almost there. Keep working hard and make this month, in your honor, count.

Superintendent Carpenter

post_text: Hello fellow tigers! I wanted to ask you to join me in hanging your American flag today, and every day, for the duration of this frightening and bizarre battle. Our flag’s colors stand for unity, strength, hardiness, valor, vigilance, and perseverance – qualities we all need in spades to not only overcome the outbreak, but to rebuild our communities as we begin to move forward from its effects. Hanging our flags will also be a way to both visually show our support for one another and demonstrate our pride for those who are putting their personal needs and wants second for the greater good.

post_text:
Why the Governor Made the Decision She Did:
She wanted to do everything she could to keep families safe. She made this decision to minimize spread. The attached graph shows the benefit of social isolation and one of the main reasons why taking this action will help at this time. The ideas of this is to flatten the curve and allow our health system in the community to continue to operate and not become overwhelmed.



Even with schools closed this idea of social distancing works only if we, over the next three weeks, do exactly that. Stay away from large gatherings and minimize contact with others. We need to make sure we continue with the good practices of washing hands and covering coughs. Do not panic, instead use caution. We’re all in this together, and taking these steps will help our community.
If you have any health related questions the state hotline number is, 1-855-600-3453. Once you call you will be routed to different health experts. If you have other questions about schools, supplies, child care etc.,
call 1-833-551-0518.

post_text:
Message from Superintendent Kirk Carpenter:

We are canceling all out of state travel for a minimum of the next 45 days (April 30). This includes all athletics, activities and employee travel.

Spring Break is approaching with a heightened awareness for COVID-19 (commonly known as Coronavirus). AMSD will be doing deep cleaning at all school sites during spring break. While schools are being cleaned, all AMSD schools will be closed to employees and visitors beginning at 6 p.m. on Friday, March 13, 2020. Schools will reopen on Monday, March 23, 2020 at 6 a.m.

This notification does not apply to other locations Plant Operations, Central Office, Transportation, Technology, Exceptional Programs or to custodial staff.

Should there be a need to update employees on COVID-19 in our community during Spring Break, employees will be emailed and updates will be posted on our website.

NMPED strongly discourages all student and staff travel both in-state and out-of-state.

More information will be shared here concerning travel out of state and in high risk areas as it becomes available.

post_text:
Thank you Citizens of Aztec. The mil money you all vote on is used for programs like this and here is some direct feedback of how our kids are using it.
"CV Koogler is averaging 54 Reading lessons and is in the Top 5 of Schools in New Mexico for Reading Lessons Completed! You are number 2 in our state (out of 90 schools) and students have read over 1.5 million words! You might enjoy the attached graphic which shows word counts of popular books. The students have been working really hard to meet their goals. Thank you also to the teachers for their leadership using this program.

Thank you for your efforts and commitment to use Reading Plus with great fidelity! Please stay in touch with ways I may assist.
"

post_text: We want to wish everyone a Happy Holiday season. We also recognize these can be emotional times for families. As we go into Winter Break, we would like to share some resources that might be of use to students and parents: the "Say Something" app or the Crisis Text Line which can be reached by texting "home" to 741741 are still available during the break. Also attached are some additional resources.
